r  ."]},{"name":"Howton","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Houghton  ."]},{"name":"Hufton","meanings":["English: habitational name; probably from Stony Houghton in Pleasley (Derbyshire), the name of which derives from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Houghton  ."]}]},{"name":"Randolph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman given name, Old Norse <i>Rannulfr</i>, derived from <i>rand</i> ‘rim, shield’ (or <i>hrafn</i> ‘raven’) + <i>úlfr</i> ‘wolf’."],"variants":[{"name":"Randulf","meanings":["From a Norman given name, Old Norse <i>Rannulfr</i>, derived from <i>rand</i> ‘rim, shield’ (or <i>hrafn</i> ‘raven’) + <i>úlfr</i> ‘wolf’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":18,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":38,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":48,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, 